==English==
===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/'ævəɻəs/}}
*{{audio|en-us-avarice.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Etymology===
From {{OF.}}, from {{L.}} ''[[avaritia]]'', from ''[[avarus]]'' (greedy), from ''[[avere]]'' (to desire).

===Noun===
'''avarice'''
#An [[excessive]] or inordinate [[desire]] of gain; [[greed]]iness after wealth; [[covetousness]]; [[cupidity]].
#An [[inordinate]] desire for some supposed good.
#One of the [[seven deadly sins]].

====Quotations====
;excessive desire of gain
{{timeline|
1600s=1606|
1700s=1726 1776}}
*'''1606''' — [[Shakespeare]], ''[[s:The_Tragedy_of_Macbeth|Macbeth]] iv 3''
*:With this there grows,
*:In my most ill-compos'd affection, such 
*:A stanchless '''avarice''', that, were I king, 
*:I should cut off the nobles for their lands.
*'''1726''' — [[w:Jonathan Swift|Jonathan Swift]], ''[[s:Gulliver's Travels|Gulliver's Travels]] Part II, ch. vi''
*:Whether they were always so free from '''avarice''', partialities, or want, that a bribe, or some other sinister view, could have no place among them? 
*'''1776''' — [[w:Thomas Paine|Thomas Paine]], ''[[s:Common_Sense_(Book)|Common Sense]]''
*:Oppression is often the ''consequence'', but seldom or never the ''means'' of riches; and though '''avarice''' will preserve a man from being necessitously poor, it generally makes him too timorous to be wealthy.

